<h1>From Benjamin Franklin</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir </td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Passy Oct 5 1781</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p> I congratulate your Excellency on your Recovery.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n1" id="PJA12d006n1-ptr">1</a> I hope this Seasoning will be the means of securing your future Health, by accomodating your Constitution to the Air of that Country. </p>
<p>Here are Advices from Admiral de Grasse, which left him the 13th of August coming out of Straits of Bahama, with 28 Sail, of the Line; bound to Chesapeak Bay: unless he should meet at Sea a call to N. York from General Washington. He took with him from the Islands 3,600 Land Troops, which with his marines make near 6,000 Men capable of acting either against Cornwallis or in the Siege of New York: and the 8 Sail under M. de Barras at Boston joining him will make a Sea Force superior to any expected of the Enemy in those Seas, so that we may hope for some good News from that Quarter.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n2" id="PJA12d006n2-ptr">2</a></p>
<p> Since the Letter your Excellency honourd me with of the 25 of August, I have learnt nothing new of the Mediation. It seems to be <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0004">[4]</span> at present in a State of Stagnation. Any farther Proceedings in it that may come to my Knowledge shall be immediately communicated to you. This Court appears attentive not only to the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Interest</span> of the United States, but to their <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Honour</span>. England seems not yet tired enough of the War to think seriously of an Accommodation, and till then our new Commission will hardly afford us much Employment, or make it necessary for us to appoint a Secretary in its Service: I send however enclosed a Copy of the Minute of Congress relating to that Appointment.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n3" id="PJA12d006n3-ptr">3</a> I have not heard of M. Danas Arrival at Petersburg: If your Excelly has receivd any communicable Advices from him, I shall be glad to see them, and to know whether he is likely to continue there. Enclosed is a Letter for him, and another for yourself:<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n4" id="PJA12d006n4-ptr">4</a> they appear to me to have been opened; but they are in the State I received them under Cover from M. Nesbitt of LOrient. </p>
<p> A Letter from America that has been shown me, mentions a Resolution of Congress to exchange General Burgoyne for Mr. Laurens; but I have never seen that Resolution. Do you know any thing of it? I have a Letter from Mr Burke on the Subject of that General, which I am at a loss to answer.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n5" id="PJA12d006n5-ptr">5</a></p>
<p> I received Mr. Thaxters Letter relating to the Mast-Contracts,<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n6" id="PJA12d006n6-ptr">6</a> and communicated it to Mr. de Vergennes, who I suppose will write about that Affair to M. de la Luzerne. Is it possible that a Project of supplying England with that Article from any of the <del title="deleted text">&lt;Inhabitants of the&gt;</del> United States can be executed? I have no Conception of the Means. </p>
<p>I am glad to hear that the Loan from Holland is likely to succeed:<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n7" id="PJA12d006n7-ptr">7</a> for without it, those obtaind here for our Service will not afford Payment of the List shown me the other Day by M. Grand, of your Acceptations falling due in Novr. December, January and February next, amounting to Bo.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n8" id="PJA12d006n8-ptr">8</a> 217,932.2/3. It is a Demand I had no previous Knowledge of, and therefore I hope it is not expected of me to answer it. I have accepted the Bills mentioned in yours of the 24th past<a class="ptr" href="#PJA12d006n9" id="PJA12d006n9-ptr">9</a> as drawn by you upon me on that day: But the great Sum abovementioned it will be out of my Power to accept if you should draw for it, no Provision being made for it in our last Grants. </p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="salute">With great Respect, I have the honour to be, Sir, Your most obedient and most humble Servant</p>
<p class="signed">B Franklin</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="PJA12d006sn1">
<p>
<span class="docSource"><span class="dType"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr></span> (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>); endorsed by John Thaxter: Dr. Franklin 5th. Octr. 1781.</span>
</p>
</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n1-ptr" id="PJA12d006n1">1</a>
<p>Franklin received reports from C.W.F. Dumas and Jean de Neufville &amp; Fils (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Benjamin Franklin&lt;/i&gt;, ed. Leonard W. Labaree, William B. Willcox (from vol. 15), Claude A. Lopez (vol. 27), Barbara B. Oberg (from vol. 28), Ellen R. Cohn (from vol. 36), and others, New Haven, 1959.  ]">Franklin, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers</span></span>, 35:478, 510511).</p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n2-ptr" id="PJA12d006n2">2</a>
<p>De Grasses fleet reached Chesapeake Bay on 30 Aug., but at the Battle of the Chesapeake on 5 Sept., the French advan-<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="ADMS-06-12-02-pb-0005">[5]</span>tage was less than Franklin envisioned. This was owing to the detachment of four ships from the fleet to support the siege at Yorktown and the absence of Barras, who did not arrive until the 10th. The French margin, therefore, was 24 ships of the line to 19 for the British. Tactically the battle was indecisive, but de Grasse prevented the British fleet under Adm. Thomas Graves from entering the bay and thus gained a strategic victory. Barras arrival with siege artillery for Rochambeaus army made the French position impregnable and sealed the fate of Cornwallis army (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Piers Mackesy, &lt;i&gt;The War for America, 17751783&lt;/i&gt;, Cambridge, 1965. ]">Mackesy, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">War for America</span></span>, p.423425; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Alfred Thayer Mahan, &lt;i&gt;The Major Operations of the Navies in the War of American Independence&lt;/i&gt;, Boston, 1913. ]">Mahan, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Navies in the War of Amer. Independence</span></span>, p.178184). </p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n3-ptr" id="PJA12d006n3">3</a>
<p>On 26 June Congress named Francis Dana, until such time as he could proceed to Russia, secretary to the ministers appointed to negotiate a peace treaty. Should Dana not be available, a majority of the ministers were authorized to appoint a secretary (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington C. Ford and others, eds., &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;, Washington, 19041937; 34 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 20:699). The enclosure has not been found, but a copy in William Temple Franklins hand is in Lb/JA/15, and was presumably done during young Franklins service as secretary during the peace negotiations in 1782 or 1783 (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers, Microfilms</span>, Reel No. 103).</p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n4-ptr" id="PJA12d006n4">4</a>
<p>From James Lovell, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-11-02-0282" class="document">21 July</a> (vol. 11:381383). The letter to Dana has not been identified.</p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n5-ptr" id="PJA12d006n5">5</a>
<p>This sentence was interlined at the end of the paragraph. Edmund Burkes appeal on Burgoynes behalf was dated 15 August. Franklin replied on 15 Oct., by which time he had received a copy of Congress resolution of 14 June authorizing him to exchange Gen. Burgoyne for Henry Laurens, which he enclosed in his letter to Burke (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Benjamin Franklin&lt;/i&gt;, ed. Leonard W. Labaree, William B. Willcox (from vol. 15), Claude A. Lopez (vol. 27), Barbara B. Oberg (from vol. 28), Ellen R. Cohn (from vol. 36), and others, New Haven, 1959.  ]">Franklin, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers</span></span>, 35:362365, 594; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington C. Ford and others, eds., &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;, Washington, 19041937; 34 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 20:647648). For additional information on the proposed exchange, see the letter of <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-12-02-0182" class="document">5 March 1782</a> from Robert R. Livingston, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-12-02-0182&amp;expandNote=PJA12d212n6#PJA12d212n6" class="document">note 6</a>, below; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Henry Laurens&lt;/i&gt;, ed. Philip M. Hamer, George C. Rogers Jr., and David R. Chesnutt (from vol. 5), David R. Chesnutt and C. James Taylor (from vol. 11), and others, Columbia, S.C., 19682003; 16 vols. ]">Laurens, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers</span></span>, vol. 15, passim.</p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n6-ptr" id="PJA12d006n6">6</a>
<p>Thaxter to Franklin, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-11-02-0351" class="document">30 Aug.</a> (vol. 11:472473). </p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n7-ptr" id="PJA12d006n7">7</a>
<p>The origin of this erroneous report is unknown.</p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n8-ptr" id="PJA12d006n8">8</a>
<p>Banco florins, the money in which accounts were kept, enjoyed approximately a four percent premium over the regular circulating florin (John J. McCusker, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Money and Exchange in Europe and America, 16001775: A Handbook</span>, Chapel Hill, 1978, p.43). </p>
</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA12d006n9-ptr" id="PJA12d006n9">9</a>
<p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ letterbook copy (Letterbook copies are normally unsigned, but any such copy is assumed to be in the hand of the person responsible for the text unless it is otherwise described.) ]">LbC</abbr>, <span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>.</p>
</div>
